I'm Raghu Marcus, your host for this program, for this podcast. Here we are. I'm sorry folks, I actually missed a week or so. Not much longer than that. That's because I had to go to a convention and the convention was of the Social Venture Network and that is entrepreneurs who gather together to figure out how to properly use their energy and resources to advance social causes, do good social action. And Ramdas has advised this organization in its earliest days, probably up till he had the stroke 15 years ago or so. And I went there to represent the Love Serve Remember Foundation, see who's interested in supporting us and see how we can support them. All of this being fairly new to me now and it brought up a lot of my own back and forth shall we say about politics, spirituality and social action. And this particular talk, actually it's an interview Ramdas gave that I found in 1979, it was July and somehow they couldn't find a studio or wherever this person was from. Her name is Dr. Patricia Hunt Perry. Never heard of her, still don't know, haven't asked Ramdas who she is. But I was taken by, she asked some really great questions and why I brought this Social Venture Network thing up is that she asked Ramdas specifically about the intersection of politics and spirituality from in the 60s and 70s and how did he feel was there an intersection and so on. And he basically talked about a real polarization between the spiritual community and the political community that in the 60s the whole acid and psychedelic thing and hate Ashby was basically a spiritual movement. But that within that movement there was political action going on. So he talked about that, it's really incisive stuff about that. It's a subject that's really come up as we've gone through this election and so on and so forth about how to take action and yet come from a spiritual base. Now, I myself, as I said about being, I had some trebidation going to this Social Venture Network gathering. I just feel like every time I've gone to or been close to or involved with people who are really wanting to change this world and grab it by the throat and change it, I've always had misgivings about that. Now, gee, maybe some of this is my laziness about getting out there and getting on the streets. Well, it's not necessarily getting out in the streets but that's part of it. So, there's some complexity involved here in terms of your personality and so on. But I always did think that going out there and raging against the machine, to use a little quip for a band, it can't be productive unless you really are coming from a place where it's not us and them and that is a very, very difficult thing. So, this has been a conundrum for me and in this particular gathering of the Social Venture Network people, there was a lot of breakout groups that they had and a lot of encountering and people sharing with which I thought was pretty marvelous and it led me to have to be involved in a way that I don't normally involve myself with strangers. It turns out they weren't strangers. So, that was a very positive thing. But one of the things they asked was, what can you envision doing and seeing years down the road having an effect on culture and society, a positive effect? And being that I'm involved with, as a director of this foundation and involved with what Ramdas and what we have represented through our experience in India with Maharaji and so on and the work that we've done. I said the only thing I know we can offer is to take inner action, take action that allows us to develop compassionate heart so that we are not seeing people as other and that when we protest against that which they represent, which we feel is negative towards humans and our fellow humans, but if we can still hold that compassionate heart with them, then we can actually see real change happen. And that made me, again, think harder about some of my personally what I have done, where I have shied away from taking social action because of feeling like those people are just, they're yelling for peace in a way that's like, oh, I want to kill you to get peace. I've always shied away from that kind of thing, but as I was saying this stuff and that happens a lot, you start to express yourself and you realize certain things in yourself only through that expression, which is why some of this encounter stuff can be useful, but just start to realize, I need to do more of that. I need to engender more of that compassionate heart. I need to stop hating Paul Ryan. He's very difficult. Ram Dass talks about putting people, he had Bush on his pooja, on his altar forever just trying to reach the soul rather than be angry at the incarnation. So interesting stuff. I just wanted to quote, the world is a reflection of the inner turmoil and confusion of an individual. So talking about the polarization between spiritual and political people, the world is a reflection of the inner turmoil and confusion that one has day to day that you need to transform. You have to work on yourself first before you can work on the world. And I think that's a key, key point here. People, political people became more, become more conscious. The state of being is a part of political actions. So that has to be realized. Spiritual people need to honor your incarnation, our incarnation, accept your role. So I think those are two really key statements about what social action political people absolutely need to work on themselves. And spiritual people need to realize they're in the world and there is something to do and you need to honor that particular role. And in talking about developing the spiritual people to take part in social action, you need to develop the compassion at heart. And even that just then, understanding what compassion is. I mean, we all have ideas. A lot of it I have found in myself is like feeling bad for someone's plight. But this is, compassion is beyond feeling just bad. And here in this particular description, which is a great one, of course, Ram Dass does synthesize stuff in a way that we can all understand. Development of compassion is a combination. It's a combination of human feelings of being in the world and feelings, you know, that individual, you feel the pain, the suffering, the hope and the joy and the sadness wrapped up that we all have at one point or another. But at the same time, there's an equanimity of mind seeing that it's all a dance and it's perfectly part of the universe, God, whatever you want to call it, it's planned law. It's part of the law, it's part of the unfolding. So you have that in mind as you are having this complete empathetic feeling of what your neighbor is going through. So it's the balance, it's that balance where compassion lies. And I think that is so to the point and that's what, yeah, we all need to work towards that balance. And, you know, we all need to take part in what's going on around us, not just living in a cave and getting ourselves straight. Of course, that is entirely important. But I know in my own life, I have maybe shied away from taking any kind of social action or being involved. Also, I'm from Canada, which is a very apolitical place. Growing up, it just wasn't part of our lexicon whatsoever. But, you know, I've lived here for a long time and I notice I have shied away from some of this. So the universe has been dictating to me to be way more aware of the role and honor it, you know, just being part of, here's where I am and I am here. And there is a lot of injustice and there is a lot of negative action going on from the climate stuff to God knows what, huh? Be here in the middle of New York in a parking lot. Any space is good for you. I've been thinking a lot lately about what's ahead for people on both a spiritual and perhaps a political level. In the 70s we worked on ourselves in a consciousness kind of way and that in the 80s perhaps these two movements would come together. Do you see anything like this? Well, I see something, I think I word it somewhat differently and I would time label it differently because certainly the 60s were the period of LSD and the hate Ashbury and that wasn't political in large part, that was spiritual and consciousness and there also was a lot of political activism and that was a very fruitful, exciting, powerful time in the 60s and we're still sort of reverberating from that. The problem that happened in the 60s was it polarized between the spiritual and political people and that the political people felt, look, we've got to, you can't go work on yourself when you're sitting in the middle of a mess that could explode anytime, we've got to clean up the world first before we work on ourselves and the spiritual people felt that the world is a reflection of the inner turmoil in people and the inner confusion and you have to work on yourself first in order to work on the world. So that it polarized and I remember having very sort of angry discussions with people like Jerry Rubin and Allen Ginsberg and people like that. Now here it is 10 years later and we watch what happened to the Chicago 8 or 9 and we see that people like Renee Davis went with Guru Maharaji and Allen Ginsberg is a student of Trungpa Rinpoche and
